Kuratowski's proof?

A line segment connecting two points on a special kind of curve (non-self-intersecting and non-self-touching, with no cusps) is called a "secant". Since, according to the problem statement, no three points, including the bridge's endpoints, are collinear, each pair of points can have at most one secant.
Take four points $A, B, C,$ and $D$ on the curve, and consider their six secants $\overline{AB}, \overline{AC}, \overline{AD}, \overline{BC}, \overline{BD},$ and $\overline{CD}$. These six line segments can be intersecting pairs of secants, and each pair of secants can intersect at most once.
We can consider the points of intersection of secants as vertices of a graph. To avoid counting the same intersection twice, between any two points on the curve there is at most one secant and thus at most one vertex in the graph. The number of vertices of the graph can be made to decrease by one every time a pair of points is selected to connect via secant. Since each pair of secants has at most one point of intersection, this can only happen until no vertices of the graph exist.
